5_Dynamic_Programming

Solution approach to MDPs using Bellman Eqn
Use most recent V in loop
First find Value function with Prediction Problem
Then look at Control Problem to find Optimal Policy
1st) Random for Bellman... pi(a | s)
NOT... p(s',r | s,a) which refers to action giving random next state
2nd) Deterministic: go directly to goal OR go directly to losing state
Solve random and deterministic
Using current policy gives its state-value function
If there's a better action, change policy
find pi' with bigger Q or V
Greedy. Just keep working till Done
Iterative Evaluation of Value Func and Policy
policy_iteration.py
Switch between loops until done (value and policy loops)
pi(a | s) = prob of taking action a in state s
p(s',r | s,a) = prob of going to s' from s taking action a
May not go direction attempted (i.e. non-deterministic)
policy_iteration_random.py
NOTE: High penalty per step encourages SUICIDE
(Previous Technique was Policy Iteration)
Detect constant policy NOT convergence
Combine policy and value
Update IN-PLACE on iterations
Does policy improvement and evaluation
value_iteration.py
Prediction Problem: Find Value Function GIVEN a Policy
Control Problem: Find Optimal Policy and Optimal Value Function
Involves looping through all states (inefficient and not always possible)
Asychronouse DP loops through a few (or one) states
Alternate Policy Evaluation and Policy Improvement
Converge whan Bellman true (V(s) = RHS) for greedy selection
DP avoids exponention growth
Bootstrapping: Making initial guesses
MC doe NOT require bootstrapping. TD DOES require bootstrapping
